{"/service/ndnp/mthi/batch_mthi_juniper_ver01/data/sn85053305/00340581932/1923090701/0274.xml":{"full_text":"A\n\nm\ns\nI\n\u2022y\n*9*\nX\nm\nPrize Winning Meats\nYou can come here shopping with the utmost confidence\nthat the Meat you get will be the best to be obtained\nanywhere.\nAnd no matter what cut you want, you will find us\nalways willing to do our best to give it to you.\nPRICES ALWAYS CONSISTENT WITH QUALITY\n\u2014PHONE 17\u2014\nThe New Market\nFRED FORMAN, Prop.\nA Lucky Escape\u2014\nONE SATURDAY EVENING a man made a\npurchase of $40.00 worth of goods, to be paid\nfor in three monthly payments.\nWhen he went to make the last payment he\nwas surprised to learn that the store wanted\n$27.00 rather than $13.30 which he expected\nto pay. They claimed only one payment had\nbeen made.\nThis man came to the bank to ask our advice.\nHe said he was sure he had paid the bill\u2014that\nhe remembered writing a check for the pay\nment.\nIt took but a minute or two to find that can\ncelled check.\nOf course the store gladly corrected their mis\ntake when they saw this cancelled check. Mis\ntakes occur once in a while no matter how care\nful you are. But you will never have to pay\nan account twice when you can show r a proper\nly cancelled check to prove that you have act\nually paid as you claim.\nTHE\nFirst National Bank\nMember Federal Reserve System\nPLENTYWOOD, MONT.\nWe have the best equip\nped line of Drugs and\nAccessories in Northeast\nern Montana\nAt The\nPlentywood Drug\n\u2666S* A\nv\ni'f\nJ. B. SIMPSON, Inc.\nn\nO\nCHICAGO, ILL.\nHIGH GRADE\u2014\nl\n\nI\nSUITS and OVERCOATS\n\nMADE TO ORDER\nALL WOOL FABRICS\n\nAll One Price $31.50\nTHEY ARE THE BEST CLOTHES IN AMERICA\nAT THE PRICE\nJ\nFor Appointment, Phone or Write\nCHRIST PAULSON,\nReserve, Mont.\nWho Will Be The Princess?\nAnd Get Free Trip To State Fair\n\n9 9\nWILL TEST STATUTE\nON REDEMPTION OF\nTAX SALE PROPERTY\nSHERIDAN COUNTY CASE, AT\nTACKING VALIDITY OF LAW,\nGOES TO HIGH COURT.\nHelena, Aug. 27.\u2014Determination of\nthe constitutionality of an act of the\nEighteenth legislative assembly relat\ning to the redemption of property\nfrom tax sale has been put up to the\nsupreme court in an appeal case from\nSheridan County.\nEarly in May an affidavit in support\nof an application for a writ of man\nws filed In the district court\nby Arthur E. Erickson, a county at\ntorney of Sheridan county, against\ni D. J. Olson, as treasurer of that coun\nty, in which Erickson set out that the\ncounty treasurer is required by Sec\ntion 2175, Revised Codes, to add 10\nper cent penalty on delinquent taxes,\nand by Section 2221, Revised Codes,\nto collect interest on delinquent taxes\nat the rate of one per cent per omnth.\nHe further sets out that the Eigh\nteenth legislative assembly enacted\nChapter 63, which was the enactment\nof house bill 335 introduced by Troy,\nof Hill county, under which owners\nof real estate are permitted to redeem\nproperty sold to the county for delin\nquent taxes, by payment of the orig\ninal tax plus seven per cent interest\nfrom date of sale.\nThe county attorney charged that\nchapter 63 is unconstitutional because\nit contravenes section 39, article 5 of\nthe state constitution, and further\ncharged it to be unconstitutional be\nI cause it denies to citizens and tax\npayers equal protection of the laws.\nHe asked for a writ of mandate re\nuamus\nstraining the county treasurer from\nj carrying out the provisions of Chap\n1 ter 63, and requiring him to observe\nI and abide by the provisions of section\n2,175 and 2, 221 of the Revised Codes.\nUpon this application an alternative\nwrit was issued by Judge C. E. Comer,\nI returnable May 19 at Plentywood. At\nthe time fixed for the eharing Judge\nC. D. Borton, presiding, sustained the\nmotion of the respondent to quash the\nalternative writ whereupon the relat\nor took an appeal to the supreme\ncourt.\nLOW WAGES CAUSE\nINFANT MORTALITY\nTT\nWashington. Poverty, employment\nof mothers outside the home, and\nhousing below the proper standard\nare three of the nrincinal cause* of\naie iniee 01 me pnncipai causes 01\ninfant mortality, according to the\nchildren's bureau Denartment of La\ncniiciren s ouieau, uep^rmeni 01 ud.\nbor, which has concluded an investi\nn-otion into infant mortality in Ralti\n^ation into infant mortality in Haiti\nmore.\n\"New evidence is afforded by the\nBaltimore study that poverty is an\nimportant factor in infant mortality,\"\nthe bureau announces,\ndifferences in color and nationality,\nand, considering only the babies born\nto native white mothers, the facts\nshowed that infant mortality rose as\nthe father's wages fell. In the poor\nest families studied about one baby in\nsix died within the year; in the most\nprosperous families about one baby in\ntwenty-six died within the year.\nEmployment of the mother away\nfrom home during pregnancy (which\nwas chiefly in factory work) was ac\ncompanied by a high percentage of\npremature births and high infant mor\ntality, especially from the causes pe\nculiar to early infancy. Employment\nof mothers away from the home dur\ning the first year of their babies' lives\nalso markedly increased the hazard to\nthe baby. Room congestion and lack\nof sanitary equipment in the house\nwere accompanied by death rates\nabove the average.\"\nLow mortality rates, approximately\nthose in New Zealand, which has the\nlowest in the world, were found among\nthe babies of foreign-born Jewish\nI mothers and in families of the high\nj est earning groups.\nEliminating\nFOR SALE\nCHEAP\nOne McCormick\n1 2 foot cut\nPUSH HARVESTER\nAlso Have\nHeader Attachment\nJ. 0. Johnson\nMedicine Lake, Mont.\nTo know\nhow good a cigarette\nreally can be tnad^\nyou must try a\nm-.\n\nj\ni\nHa 4^' S\nM\nA\n9\na fe\nB la a\n\nVlTSTOAST ED\n-1\nECONOME\nNEWSSERVICE\nBy LELAND OLDS\n(Federated Press Industrial Editor)\nANTHRACITE NOTES\nWhy have the union representatives\nrefused arbitration of their demands\non the anthracite operators?\nEvery miner knows that he was\ndoublecrossed by the public represent\native who was chairman of the 1920\narbitration board. The subservience\nof this hanger-on of the capitalist\nsystem has cost anthracite workers at\nleast $30,000,000 in wages which were\nrightfully theirs.\nRecent antics of the Railway Labor\nBoard have confirmed this deep seated\ndetermination not to accept arbitra\ntion. Only a year ago this board de\nThree years ago the anthracite coal\ncommissLon began by ruling out exhib- j\nits that touched the antnracue mon- j\nopoly in the sensitive spot of profits.\nThus the miners case was stripped of i\nits most important proof of the abd\nity of the industry to pay the increases\nwithout increasing the price of coal\nt\u00b0the consumer. J\nIhe chairman centered proceedings I\ncreed that a living wage must wait un\ntil the railroads were satisfied with\nprofits ,and proceeded to lead the Wall\nStreet attempt to substitute company\nunions for the independent shoperaft\nunions on the railroads.\nI on the question of changes in the cost\nI of living and then reoudiated the re\ncommendations of his own economist\nJ that the cost cf living justified a 27\nper cent i ncrease am i handed the min\nI P1 lbp ran f 17 npv rpn t which had!\n1 u tne scant 1 /per cent wnicn naa 1\nbeen offered by the operators and by 1\nthp c PC retarv af labor nrior to sub\necr< 4 ai ot labor prior to sun\nmisslon 0 f the dispute to arbitration.\nThis last arbitration performance in\n1 j aroitrauon peTTormance in\nt he m d u? try was a striking illustra\ntion of the subservience of so-called\nimpartial chairmen to the financial\noverlords who can make or break the\nsnug career of reasonable success and\ncomfort dreamed of by the American\nmiddle class. This 'impartial chair\nman had agreed to accept the findings\nof an economist engaged to collect\ndata on the cost of living. When the\nfindings turned out to favor a 27 per\ncent increase the operators commis\nsioner objected and the economist was\nfired. Ov^er a week-end the chairman\nreached the 17 per cent verdict.\nAccording to Kauschenbush in his\nbook, The Anthracite Question, pro\nminers are puzzled to know just how\nthis chairman happened to hit upon\nthe 17 per cent and what mysterious\ninfluences worked upon \"the mind of\nthe representative of the public to\nmake him act in the peculirr way he\ndid.\"\nIt is first hand knowledge that such\nmysterious influences do work on the\nminds of representatives of the public\nthat underlies the solid opposition of\nthe miners to arbitration.\nj\nMore than 30 items for which an-,\nthracite operators check off payment\nfrom miner's earnnigs were listed in\na communication to the U. S. coal\nWorkers agreed to abandon its de 1\nmand for a check-off provision in the\nnext contract providing that the op\nerators agreed to abandon their age\nlong practice of checking off from 1\ntheir employes payment for the long\nlist of items noted.\nAmong the items for which the op\nerators have applied the check-off are\nhouse rent, insurance premiums, coal,\ntaxes, hospital and medical charges,\nexplosive supplies, pay of check\nweighmen, wages to laborers, liberty\nbonds, red cross contributions, contri\nbutions to war chests, etc. The min\ners' statement says that the operators\n\"seemingly arrogate to themselves the\nexclusive right to be the beneficiary\nof the practice\" in spite of their de\nnunciation of the suggestion that the\nnine workers participate as unfair, il\nlegal and un-American.\nThe union called the attention of the\nU. S. coal commission to the fact that\nsecret agents of the operators are in\nthe field attempting to create a situ\nation where a strike in the anthracite\nfields would be unavoidable. Accord\ning to the protest filed with the com\nmission, anthracite communities \"are\ninfested with a horde of private de\ntectives and secret agents obviously\nemployed by some of the anthracite\nproducing companies and by the bitu\nminous coal operators in the non-union\nfields. Many of /these are men of low\nmentality and equally low r moral\nstandards and come from that near\ncriminal type of private detectives de\nscribed by William J. Burns, head of\nthe U. S. Secret Service as being the\n'most scrupulous scoundrels in the\nworld.'\nIn discussing these charges Lewis\nasserted that some of these detectives\nwere in the pay of the Lehigh Coal Co.\nof which Warriner, spokesman of the\noperators is president. He said that\nstatements \u00c4bout the miners revolting\nagainst the check-off came entirely\nfrom these detectives. \"Not a single\none cf the 400 anthracite locals,\" he\nsaid \"have taken a position opposite\nto that of the officers of the union.\nScores have adopted resolutions in\nfavor of it.\"\nTry a Want Ajd, it brings results.\nCOOLIDGE\nSOFT PEDALS\nBy MARX LEWIS\nFederated Press tSaff Correspondent.\nWashington. President Coolidge\nprefers not to have his administration\nidentified too closely with the pro\ngram which the chamber of commerce\nhas recommended to him, if white\nhouse efforts to soft pedal the pro\ngram are to be taken seriously.\nTaken in connection with the re\nports that Coolidge is considering the\nsuggestion that he make a tour of the\nmiddle west some time in November,\nbefore congress convenes, \"it appears\nthat the business men's program is re\ngarded as an obstacle to the develop\nment of the president's political as\npirations in 1914.\nOne of the questions upon which the\ncommittee, headed by Julius H. aBr\nnes, president of the chamber, submit\nted a recommendation relates to\nAmerican membership in the self\nperpetuating international court. This\nI revives a problem which is causing!\n1 considerable difficulty within the Re-1\npublican party, and the appeal of the\nbankers and oil magnates that the U.\nS. join is not likely to be considered i\nuntil the matter is thrashed out with\nin the Republican organization.\nAmong the domestic issues the\nchamber of commerce made sugges -1\ntions upon, are railroad transportation, j\nin which it pleaded for private owner\nship and operation, the ship subsidy,\nin which it urged that another effort\nbe made to have congress supply pri\nvate owners vyith government funds\nfor the establishment of a privately\nowned merchant marine, taxation, in\nwhich the elimination of taxes that\nfall most heavily on the rich be re\npealed or reduced and the decreased\nrevenues obtained by a sales tax, im\nmigration, and the bonus, to which it j\nis ofyosed.\nWhile the program is one which the j\nadministration would ordinarily sup -1\nport in any event, with the exception, j\npossibly, of the bonus for war vet\nerans> the administration is anxious\nto avo j j becoming identified with pro\np 0 g a ls likely to alienate at once the\nprogressive states of the middle west.\njf tbe president makes the tr?p to the j\nmiddle west it will be with the hope 1\n\u00b0f persuading the rebellious voters;\nthere that he is not as reactionary as\nhe has been pictured.\nWHEAT PRICE\nHITS BUSINESS\nSedalia Mo \\ug 28_Low wheat\nug\nprl ces are already depressing Amen\nra business Genre-e C Jewett e-en-!\n1 Dusiness J wew gen\neral man ager of the American Wheat\nGrowers' Association Inc asserted in\ni7 Association, inc., asserted in\nan address here today before the an -1\nnual convention of the Missouri Farm\ners association.\n\"The business revival of last year\nj s running up against the brick wall\nformed bv the inability of tho Amor\nica n f amer to purchase the thin^ he\nactually needs,\" Mr. Jewett declared.\n'/American business might as well\nhave the facts straight,\" he continued.\n\"There are ten or twelve agricultural I\nstatea wherein wheat is the crop of\nma j or importance from one standpoint\nof purchasing powers. So long as\nwheat prices are low, farmers will not\nbe able to buy and wheat prices to\ndav are from 30 to 50 cents a bushel\nbelow cost of production.\n\"There is only one way in which\nwheat prices can be brought to a leg\nitimate basis, and that is the estab\nlishment of a domestic American mar\nket, independent of world prices.\"\nELEVATOR AT NASHUA\nDESTROYED BY BLAZE\nGlasgow, Aug. 27.\u2014Fire of un\nknown origin completely destroyed the\nOccident elevator at Nashua Saturday\nnight. Sparks flying from the fire\nthreatened the entire business section,\nand bad gained such headway that the\nvolunteer fire brigade was unable to\nThe fire was discovered at 10 o'clock\ncheck it, as the town has no water sup\nply f. or fire protection.\n_\nTrv a Want Ad\u2014It brings Results,\n10 cents a line per issue,\nFor\nProtection\nAgainst\nFire, Lightning, Cy\nclone, Windstorm\nGet a\nPOLICY\nin\nthe\nNORTH WESTERN\nNATIONAL\nFor Rates\nSee \"Jerry\" the lit\ntle agent.\nCall or Address\nG. G. POWELL\nPlentywood, Mont.\nin\n\nv\nr\nII\nV\nii\n\u00ef,\ni\nBring the Family Here\nYou will find that the cost of a big meal, all\ncooked and served in a most delightfully\nhomey\" atmosphere, is less than the same\nDinner could be served at home. Your choice\nof the following appetizing dishes:\na\nSpecial\nCHICKEN DINNER\nFifty Cents\nThe Elgin Cafe\nPOPESKU BROS., Proprietors\nPLENTYWOOD, MONTANA\n\n\nT\n\n\nf\nt\ni\n\np\nf\no \u00ab\\tti 11 Ilf*\nV W/ nV k P cl 7\\ r\\ nf\n\u00ee VV 11 y HLR CL olClU U1\nS I 1\nN\na\nU\nI\nb\np\nI\nt\no\n\u27564\u00ab 4\u00ab\nHr* Farmer!:\ni\n\nBACON\n\nV\n\nV\nY\nFor your harvest at\nV\n\no\n\no\n30 cents per lb. I\n\n\nI\nWe still have a few\nat 25 cents\nper pound\n\nHAMS\nV\n\n\ni*\n\n\n\n\nV\n\nO\ni'f\n\nAT\n*r*\nHEINS' MARKET\nL\n\u2756\u2756'JH* HHAHf# 4 \u00bbi. ,y\n\n\nWINTER\n\n10\nV\n\n\n\n\n\nV\nO\n4\u00bb\nV\nO\n\u00bbY.\nv\nFurnace Over\nhauled. We can Please You in this line of\nwork.\nDon't forget to have\no\nyour\nV\n\n\n\nO\nV\n\n\nStove repairs ordered Now will save you\ngrief.\n\n\nV\n\n\n\nV\ni\nY\nV\nL. G. ZEIDLER\nF\ni\nHardware","height":"26976","width":"20520"}}
